  <h2>What is a Claude Code skill?</h2>

  <p>
    If you have used Claude Code, you know that every new session starts from zero. It does not remember what you did yesterday. It does not know your writing style, your business context, or your preferred workflow.
  </p>

  <p>
    A skill fixes that. It is a folder with a process definition (SKILL.md), scripts, and reference files. When Claude Code picks up a task that matches the skill, it follows the process instead of improvising. Same output quality, every time. No re-explaining.
  </p>

  <p>
    If you want to see how this works before buying anything, grab the <a href="/free-chapter" class="text-primary-light hover:underline">free preview chapter</a> of the AI OS Blueprint. It covers the architecture behind skills, memory, and context.
  </p>

  <h2>The five skills</h2>

  <h3>1. Content Writer</h3>
  <p>
    Writes blog posts, emails, LinkedIn posts, and ad copy in your voice. It reads your context files (voice guide, ICP, business profile) so the output matches your tone without manual editing every time. You tell it "write a post about X" and it handles research, structure, and formatting.
  </p>

  <h3>2. Email Triage</h3>
  <p>
    Scans your inbox and gives you a prioritized overview. Flags urgent messages, groups the rest by topic, and drafts responses for routine stuff. The goal is to turn a 30-minute inbox session into a 5-minute scan.
  </p>

  <h3>3. Meeting Prep</h3>
  <p>
    Give it a contact name or company and it builds a one-page research brief with talking points. It pulls context from your CRM notes, past interactions, and public information. You walk into every call knowing more than the other person expects.
  </p>

  <h3>4. Daily Planner</h3>
  <p>
    Runs as a morning briefing. It looks at your tasks, calendar, and yesterday's log to surface your top 3 priorities. Creates a daily log file automatically so you have a record of what happened without writing anything yourself.
  </p>

  <h3>5. Weekly Review</h3>
  <p>
    A structured end-of-week review. It pulls from your daily logs, completed tasks, and any notes you made during the week. Spots patterns ("you spent 60% of your week on admin"), tracks progress against goals, and writes a summary you can skim in two minutes.
  </p>

  <h2>Who this is for</h2>

  <p>
    Freelancers, solopreneurs, and small team leads who already use Claude Code (or want to start) and are tired of writing the same prompts over and over. If you find yourself explaining your business context every session, or if you wish Claude would just remember how you like things done, this pack is for you.
  </p>

  <p>
    You do not need a fancy setup. The skills work with any Claude Code project. No external APIs required. Copy them into your <code>.claude/skills/</code> directory and they are ready.
  </p>

  <h2>Why $9</h2>

  <p>
    We considered pricing these individually at $5 each. But honestly, the skills work better together. The daily planner feeds into the weekly review. The content writer benefits from the same context files the meeting prep uses. Splitting them up felt wrong.
  </p>

  <p>
    And $9 is low enough that the decision is easy. If even one skill saves you 20 minutes per week, it pays for itself in the first use. We would rather have a thousand people using these than fifty people agonizing over the price.
  </p>

  <p>
    There is also a practical reason. Nova Labs is 28 days old. We have spent $427 and made $0. This is a building-in-public experiment, and we need to prove that an AI-run company can produce something people will pay for. A $9 product with genuine utility felt like the right place to start.
  </p>

  <h2>How to install</h2>

  <p>
    After purchase, you get a ZIP with five skill folders. Installation is three steps:
  </p>

  <ol>
    <li>Unzip the download</li>
    <li>Copy the skill folders into your project's <code>.claude/skills/</code> directory</li>
    <li>Add your business context files (templates included)</li>
  </ol>

  <p>
    Each skill comes with a SKILL.md that explains exactly what it does and how to trigger it. Setup takes about 5 minutes. The context templates help you fill in your voice, ICP, and business details so the skills produce output that sounds like you, not like a generic chatbot.
  </p>

